WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:03.630 --> 00:00:06.920
JAMES CLEWETT: What we've done
is I've got a radiation source

00:00:06.920 --> 00:00:10.450
which is emitting a constant
stream of electrons.

00:00:10.450 --> 00:00:14.830
As neutrons are decaying into
protons, out pops an electron,

00:00:14.830 --> 00:00:19.190
and I'm counting not how many
it's giving out, but how many

00:00:19.190 --> 00:00:20.760
of them are going into
the Geiger counter.

00:00:20.760 --> 00:00:22.170
That's a slightly different
number.

00:00:22.170 --> 00:00:24.008
MALE SPEAKER: And what kind
of ballpark figures are we

00:00:24.008 --> 00:00:25.220
talking here?

00:00:25.220 --> 00:00:26.420
JAMES CLEWETT: Well--

00:00:26.420 --> 00:00:27.825
MALE SPEAKER: You must know
because [INAUDIBLE].

00:00:27.825 --> 00:00:28.150
JAMES CLEWETT: Yes.

00:00:28.150 --> 00:00:32.680
So it's about 20 per second
going into the Geiger counter.

00:00:32.680 --> 00:00:36.120
And then I'm feeding that into
this little box, which is just

00:00:36.120 --> 00:00:39.000
turning that number
into a voltage.

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:45.120
So these two wires are
collecting that voltage, and

00:00:45.120 --> 00:00:51.710
they're passing them into the
oscilloscope, where we can see

00:00:51.710 --> 00:00:53.000
the pulses as they go by.

00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:55.310
Each pulse represents
one electron.

00:00:55.310 --> 00:00:57.780
And electrons are all the same,
so those pulses are all

00:00:57.780 --> 00:00:59.820
the same height.

00:00:59.820 --> 00:01:03.390
And so as those pulses flash
by, I'm counting them, the

00:01:03.390 --> 00:01:04.410
computer is counting them.

00:01:04.410 --> 00:01:08.000
So the wire comes out of the
oscilloscope, it goes through

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:12.410
this little breakout box and
into the back of the computer.

00:01:12.410 --> 00:01:14.120
You can buy one of these
things for about 200

00:01:14.120 --> 00:01:14.690
quid, by the way.

00:01:14.690 --> 00:01:15.760
They're worth having.

00:01:15.760 --> 00:01:19.720
Into the back of the computer,
and then I've written a little

00:01:19.720 --> 00:01:20.560
computer program.

00:01:20.560 --> 00:01:23.790
And all the computer program
does is sit there for 10

00:01:23.790 --> 00:01:26.920
seconds and count pulses.

00:01:26.920 --> 00:01:27.700
That's it.

00:01:27.700 --> 00:01:29.430
It's really simple.

00:01:29.430 --> 00:01:30.520
It's all graphs today.

00:01:30.520 --> 00:01:36.940
Here's time along here, and the
stream of electrons looks

00:01:36.940 --> 00:01:39.510
something like this as they're
coming out, and they're

00:01:39.510 --> 00:01:42.090
randomly distributed, which my
stream of electrons absolutely

00:01:42.090 --> 00:01:42.630
isn't there.

00:01:42.630 --> 00:01:45.300
It's getting less random
by the second.

00:01:45.300 --> 00:01:46.910
And all I'm doing
is I'm counting.

00:01:46.910 --> 00:01:51.270
So I start with a value of 0,
and then I get to this time,

00:01:51.270 --> 00:01:53.200
and I'm adding 1.

00:01:53.200 --> 00:02:01.940
I get here, 2, 3, 4, 5,
6, 7, 8, 9, and so on.

00:02:01.940 --> 00:02:03.690
And this is where the
probability bit comes in

00:02:03.690 --> 00:02:07.690
because the chances are
that over 10 seconds--

00:02:07.690 --> 00:02:09.900
remember this graph?

00:02:09.900 --> 00:02:12.410
So the most likely number that
we're going to get here--

00:02:12.410 --> 00:02:14.610
I measured this this morning--

00:02:14.610 --> 00:02:16.345
is 216.

00:02:16.345 --> 00:02:17.260
MALE SPEAKER: Over 10 seconds?

00:02:17.260 --> 00:02:19.180
JAMES CLEWETT: Over
10 seconds.

00:02:19.180 --> 00:02:21.780
And that's just an empirical
measurement.

00:02:21.780 --> 00:02:25.480
So I'm taking the number that
I've counted up, and I'm going

00:02:25.480 --> 00:02:28.320
to subtract off 216.

00:02:28.320 --> 00:02:31.560
What we've just seen, and
whether the answer was 13,

00:02:31.560 --> 00:02:34.600
then obviously either
I've come in here--

00:02:34.600 --> 00:02:35.990
and I'm going to get
this right--

00:02:35.990 --> 00:02:43.310
I've had 229, or it could
equally be that I've been here

00:02:43.310 --> 00:02:45.210
and had 203.

00:02:45.210 --> 00:02:47.310
Both of those are going to
give the answer of 13.

00:02:47.310 --> 00:02:50.340
So the reason that's happened
is I wasn't interested in

00:02:50.340 --> 00:02:51.750
showing you a negative
random number.

00:02:51.750 --> 00:02:55.060
I wanted to show you an integer
value, a positive

00:02:55.060 --> 00:02:56.450
integer value.

00:02:56.450 --> 00:02:57.782
So I just wrote a piece
of software where

00:02:57.782 --> 00:02:59.230
I squared it up.

00:02:59.230 --> 00:03:00.130
I took the square root.

00:03:00.130 --> 00:03:03.910
The square root's inevitably
positive, and so my software

00:03:03.910 --> 00:03:05.570
is always going to give
a positive answer.

00:03:05.570 --> 00:03:06.790
I cheated.

00:03:06.790 --> 00:03:07.540
OK, I admit it.

00:03:07.540 --> 00:03:08.800
I cheated.

00:03:08.800 --> 00:03:11.020
